ce:section.ce:para:
A number of different interferences were added to assess the selectivity of our probe solution. As shown in Fig. 3
                     , we studied the influence of various interfering materials on our probe solution, including phthalic acid (PA), isophthalic acid (IPA), terephthalic acid (TPA), 2,5-pyridinedicarboxylic acid (2,5-PDCA), pyridine-3,5-dicarboxylic acid (3,5-PDCA), 2,3-pyridinedicarboxylic acid (2,3-PDCA), pyridine-3,4-dicarboxylic acid (3,4-PDCA), 2,4-pyridinedicarboxylic acid (2,4-PDCA), glutamic acid (GL), aspartic acid (AS), 3-carboxypyridine (3-CP), benzoic acid (BA), 2-carboxypyridine (2-CP), 4-carboxypyridine (4-CP), nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD). Almost these materials have carboxyl group in their structures (Fig. 4
                     ). DPA induced noticeable luminescence enhancement, while slight changes in emission was observed for other interference solutions. Thus, our probe solution was able to detect DPA while not affected by these interfering materials (Fig. 3A and B). These results confirmed that DPA was the only ligand that can sensitize luminescence of Ln in the presence of ASAP. Additionally, we also examined the effect of these interfering materials in the absence of ASAP to prove that ASAP is essential to improve the selectivity of our probe (Fig. 3C). Obvious luminescence enhancement was observed after adding these interferences, demonstrating these interferences could also coordinate and sensitize Tb3+ in the absence of ASAP.
